<article>
    <h1>Learning a new lan&#xAD;guage</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201003/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-03"><time>2020-10-03</time></a>
        - <span>CLASSIFIED&#xAD;S</span>
        - <span role="byline">By JUSTIN CHUA</span>
    </section>

    <p>Look­ing to beef up your repos­i­tory of spo­ken lan­guages? To­day’s piece dis­sects the in­tri­ca­cies of learning a new lan­guage. Shall we? Let’s!</p>
    <p>FIND YOUR MO­TIVE</p>
    <p>First off, it would be help­ful to know your rea­son be­hind pick­ing up the lan­guage. And of course, no mo­tive is more right than an­other. It could be merely be­cause you want to im­press some­one, or maybe you are af­ter a pro­mo­tion.</p>
    <p>Ei­ther way, iden­ti­fy­ing this should serve you with the nec­es­sary im­pe­tus to take on the task.</p>
    <p>FIND A LAN­GUAGE PART­NER</p>
    <p>Find your­self a part­ner whom you can prac­tise with. Be­cause com­mu­ni­ca­tion is more than just ver­bal, and in­cludes sub­tleties such as fa­cial ex­pres­sions and ges­tures, learning with a part­ner would prove more ben­e­fi­cial than say an on­line re­source.</p>
    <p>MAKE MIS­TAKES</p>
    <p>Pick­ing up a new lan­guage is a com­mend­able de­ci­sion, so no­body should be knock­ing you for mak­ing mis­takes in this re­spect. Your will­ing­ness to make mis­takes means be­ing ready to put your­self in po­ten­tially awk­ward sit­u­a­tions. While this can be daunt­ing, it is one of the most ef­fec­tive ways to de­velop and im­prove. Faux pas? Je ne sais pa!</p>
    <p>BE­GIN NOTIC­ING</p>
    <p>Whether it is pick­ing up nu­ances in pro­nun­ci­a­tion, tone, vo­cab­u­lary or gram­mar, it pays to be ob­ser­vant. Notic­ing these sub­tleties can go a long way in de­vel­op­ing a sense of cu­rios­ity within, and this might even lead you to seek ex­ter­nal sources for an ex­pla­na­tion.</p>
    <p>HAVE PA­TIENCE</p>
    <p>Be­fore tak­ing on a new lan­guage, re­mem­ber that like just about ev­ery­thing in life, mas­ter­ing the craft will take time. This jour­ney will un­doubt­edly come with its share of frus­tra­tion, but it is im­por­tant that you stick to it. Be realistic about your ex­pec­ta­tions, and slowly but surely, you will get there.</p>


